## Critical Distinctions

### Determined vs. Justified
- Being determined (ontology) ≠ being unjustified (epistemology)
- Can be determined to believe "2+2=4" and still be justified
- Mathematical reasons exist independently of causes of belief

### Analytic vs. Synthetic
- Analytic: true by definition within a language (math, logic)
- Synthetic: true in the actual world (requires empirical verification)
- Can't define objects into existence
- Ontological argument confuses these categories

### Conceptual vs. Empirical
- Conceptual: ideas in the head (logic, math, intuition)
- Empirical: external world requiring verification through predictions
- Don't mistake conceptual coherence for empirical reality

### Vicious vs. Virtuous Circularity
- Virtuous: trivial, methodologically consistent, definitional
- Vicious: unjustified ontological claims without independent evidence
- Predictive success resolves circularity

